{{Politics of Seychelles}}
A '''constitutional referendum''' was held in [[Seychelles]] on 15 November 1992. Although the proposed new constitution received the support of 54.6% of voters, it failed to pass the 60% threshold required for adoption. Subsequently a second constitutional commission was created and a second draft put to a [[Seychellois constitutional referendum, 1993|referendum]] the following year.
==Background== A constitution was drafted by a commission [[Seychellois constitutional commission election, 1992|elected]] earlier in 1992. It provided for a [[presidential system]], with presidents limited to three terms of five years. Half of the [[National Assembly (Seychelles)|National Assembly]] would be elected proportionally based on the results of presidential elections, whilst amendments to the constitution would require a referendum, with changes to some articles requiring a three-fifths majority to be approved.<ref>[http://www.sudd.ch/event.php?lang=de&id=sc011992 Seychelles, 15 November 1992: Constitution] Direct Democracy {{de icon}}</ref>
