[[File:Arms of Parker.svg|thumb|200px|Arms of Parker, Earls of Macclesfield: ''Gules, a chevron between three leopard's faces or''<ref>Debrett's Peerage, 1968, p.723</ref>]]
'''Thomas Parker, 1st Earl of Macclesfield''', {{postnominals|country=GBR|size=100%|sep=,|PC|FRS}} (23 July 1666 &ndash; 28 April 1732) was an [[England|English]] [[Whig (British political faction)|Whig]] politician.

==Youth and early career==
He was born in [[Staffordshire]], the son of Thomas Parker, an attorney at [[Leek, Staffordshire|Leek]]. He was educated at [[Adams' Grammar School]] and [[Trinity College, Cambridge]].<ref>{{acad|id=PRKR685T|name=Parker, Thomas}}</ref> He was married to Janet Carrier, whose sister was married to William Anson, [[George Anson, 1st Baron Anson|1st Baron Anson]]'s father. He was called to the bar in 1691, and became a [[Member of Parliament]] and was [[knight]]ed in 1705. In 1710 he refused the office of [[Lord Chancellor]], but was made a [[Privy Council of Great Britain|Privy Counsellor]]. He was [[Lord Chief Justice of England and Wales|Lord Chief Justice]] from 1710 to 1718 and was involved in the prosecution of [[Henry Sacheverell|Dr Sacheverell]]. He made a vehement attack on Sacheverell and the high church clergy.<ref name=aim25>[http://www.aim25.ac.uk/cgi-bin/frames/fulldesc?inst_id=13&coll_id=3645&full=1&template=1]</ref> He was also a friend of [[Bernard Mandeville|Bernard de Mandeville]], whose satirical ''Fable of the Bees'' became highly controversial in the 1720s.

He became a [[Royal Society|Fellow of the Royal Society]] in 1713. He also had a grammar school built at [[Leek, Staffordshire|Leek]], his home town. In 1714 he was raised to the peerage as '''Baron Parker of Macclesfield'''.

==Regent of Great Britain and Ireland==
[[Image:1stEarlOfMacclesfield.jpg|thumb|left|The Earl of Macclesfield, by [[Godfrey Kneller|Sir Godfrey Kneller]].]]
On 1 August 1714, [[Anne, Queen of Great Britain|Queen Anne]] died, and her successor, [[George I of Great Britain|King George I]], was in [[Electorate of Hanover|Hanover]], so Baron Parker was designated Regent of Great Britain, Ireland and the realms beyond the seas until the new monarch could be informed of the situation and take the crown. He governed until 18 September 1714. 

In 1718, because the King could not speak English, Parker gave the [[speech from the throne|King's Speech]] in the [[House of Lords]].

==Lord Chancellor==
In 1718, he became Lord Chancellor and given a pension for life, and was a favourite of the [[George I of Great Britain|King]]. In 1721, he was advanced to the title '''Earl of Macclesfield''' with the additional subsidiary title of '''Viscount Parker'''. In 1724, he was implicated in financial irregularities, but he did not resign as [[Lord Chancellor]] until 1725.

==Impeachment==
In 1725, he was [[impeachment|impeached]] and tried in the [[House of Lords]].<ref name=aim25/> He was, unanimously, convicted of corruption for taking more than £100,000 in bribes (the equivalent of more than £11,000,000 today). He was fined £30,000 and placed in the [[Tower of London]] until payment was received. He was also struck off the roll of the [[Privy Council]]. He was a fabulously wealthy man, possibly because of his corruption, but as this money was confiscated, he had no resources to pay his fine. He spent most of the rest of his life at [[Shirburn Castle]], where he was buried.

He was, however, still able to be a pallbearer at the funeral of Sir [[Isaac Newton]] in 1727. He died in [[Soho Square]], London.

